# __PROJECT_NAME__

__DESCRIPTION__

Bootstrapped with [`jararaca new`](https://github.com/LuscasLeo/jararaca).

## Requirements

- Python __PYTHON_VERSION__+
- A RabbitMQ broker and a Redis backend (a ready-to-use `docker-compose.yml` is included)

## Getting started

Create a virtual environment and install the project in editable mode with the
development dependencies:

```bash
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -e ".[dev]"
```

> Using [uv](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/)? `uv venv && uv pip install -e ".[dev]"`.

Copy the example environment file and adjust it if needed:

```bash
cp .env.example .env
```

Start the supporting infrastructure (RabbitMQ + Redis):

```bash
docker compose up -d
```

## Running

The application exposes a single `Microservice` instance (`app`) and an ASGI
app (`http_app`) in [`src/__PACKAGE_NAME__/app.py`](src/__PACKAGE_NAME__/app.py).

Run the HTTP server:

```bash
jararaca server __PACKAGE_NAME__.app:app --port 8000
```

Then open http://localhost:8000/docs for the interactive API documentation, or
hit the health endpoint:

```bash
curl http://localhost:8000/health/
```

Run the message bus worker (consumes asynchronous messages):

```bash
jararaca worker __PACKAGE_NAME__.app:app \
    --broker-url "$BROKER_URL" \
    --backend-url "$BACKEND_URL"
```

Run the scheduler (dispatches scheduled actions):

```bash
jararaca beat __PACKAGE_NAME__.app:app \
    --broker-url "$BROKER_URL" \
    --backend-url "$BACKEND_URL"
```

Declare the broker infrastructure (exchanges and queues) before the first run:

```bash
jararaca declare __PACKAGE_NAME__.app:app --broker-url "$BROKER_URL"
```

## Generating a TypeScript client

```bash
jararaca gen-tsi __PACKAGE_NAME__.app:app ./client.ts
```

## Development

```bash
ruff check .          # lint
ruff format .         # format
mypy src              # type-check
pytest                # run tests
```

